  "prompt": "Which keywords are associated with entry-level instructional design jobs?",
  "response": "When searching for entry-level instructional design jobs, there are several keywords you might want to include to improve your chances of finding suitable positions. These keywords can help to align your search with the skills and responsibilities typically associated with such roles. Here are some common keywords and phrases:\n\n1. **Instructional Design**\n2. **E-Learning**\n3. **Curriculum Development**\n4. **Learning Management System (LMS)**\n5. **Content Creation**\n6. **Storyboarding**\n7. **Multimedia Design**\n8. **Online Learning**\n9. **Training Development**\n10. **Educational Technology**\n11. **Adult Learning Principles**\n12. **ADDIE Model**\n13. **Needs Assessment**\n14. **Interactive Learning**\n15. **Course Development**\n16. **SCORM**\n17. **Articulate Storyline**\n18. **Captivate**\n19. **Learning Objectives**\n20. **Evaluation and Assessment**\n\nAdditionally, consider terms like **remote**, **junior**, or **associate** that often accompany entry-level positions. It's also helpful to look for sectors in which instructional design is prominent, such as **corporate training**, **higher education**, **K-12 education**, **nonprofits**, and **government** jobs.",
